3 Basic computer skills

This task deals with elementary plotting and computing skills needed during the rest of the course. You can use either R or Python, although R is the recommended language and we will only guarantee support in R. For documentation in R, just type ?{function name here}.

Subtask 3.a)

Plot the density function of the Beta-distribution, with mean \(\mu = 0.2\) and variance \(\sigma^2=0.01\). The parameters \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) of the Beta-distribution are related to the
mean and variance according to the following equations \[\begin{aligned} \alpha = \mu \left( \frac{\mu(1-\mu)}{\sigma^2} - 1 \right), \quad \beta = \frac{\alpha (1-\mu) }{\mu} \,.\end{aligned}\]

Potentially helpful content: Interactive Beta distribution PDF visualization

Below you can find an interactive visualization of the probability density function of the Beta distribution. You can set the two parameters of the beta distribution (\(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), see e.g.Â Wikipedia for further details). This is only meant to help you get a feel for the Beta distribution, for subtask 3.a) you will still have to plot the density function yourself.

Code 
math = require('https://unpkg.com/mathjs@5.9.0/dist/math.min.js')
xs = d3.range(0, 1, 1e-3)
viewof alpha = Inputs.input(2)
viewof beta = Inputs.input(3) 
Inputs.form([
    Inputs.bind(
        Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 2, step: 0.1, label: "alpha"}),
        viewof alpha
    ), 
    Inputs.bind(
        Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 3, step: 0.1, label: "beta"}), 
        viewof beta
    ),
], {
    template: (inputs) => htl.html`<div style="display: flex; gap: 3em">
  ${inputs}
</div>`
  })
Code 
class BetaDistribution {
    constructor(alpha, beta){
        this.alpha = alpha;
        this.beta = beta;
        this.normalizing_constant = math.gamma(alpha) * math.gamma(beta) / math.gamma(alpha + beta)
    }
    pdf(x){
        return Math.pow(x, alpha-1) * Math.pow(1 - x, beta-1) / this.normalizing_constant;
    }
    pdfs(x){
        return x.map(x => this.pdf(x));
    }
}
Plot.plot({
    marks: [
        Plot.line(d3.zip(xs, new BetaDistribution(alpha, beta).pdfs(xs))),
        Plot.ruleX([0]),
        Plot.ruleY([0]),
        Plot.text([`The PDF of the Beta(${alpha}, ${beta}) distribution`], {frameAnchor: "top", fontSize: 20, dy: -40})
    ],
    x: {label: "x"},
    y: {label: "PDF"},
    marginTop: 60, 
    style: {fontSize: "1em", width: "100%"},
})
Subtask 3.b)

Take a sample of 1000 random numbers from the above distribution and plot a histogram of the results. Compare visually to the density function.

Subtask 3.c)

Compute the sample mean and variance from the drawn sample. Verify that they match (roughly) to the true mean and variance of the distribution.

Subtask 3.d)

Estimate the central 95% probability interval of the distribution from the drawn samples.

4 Bayesâ theorem 1

A group of researchers has designed a new
inexpensive and painless test for detecting lung cancer. The test is intended to be an initial screening test for the population in general. A positive result (presence of lung cancer) from the test would be followed up immediately with medication, surgery or more extensive and expensive test. The researchers know from their studies the following facts:

  • Test gives a positive result in 98\(\%\) of the time when the test subject has lung cancer.
  • Test gives a negative result in 96 \(\%\) of the time when the test subject does not have lung cancer.
  • In general population approximately one person in 1000 has lung cancer.
Task 4

The researchers are happy with these preliminary results (about 97\(\%\) success rate), and wish to get the test to market as soon as possible. How would you advise them? Base your answer on Bayesâ rule computations.

Hint:

Relatively high false negative (cancer doesnât get detected) or high false positive (unnecessarily administer medication) rates are typically bad and undesirable in tests.

Here are some probability values that can help you figure out if you copied the right conditional probabilities from the question.

  • P(Test gives positive | Subject does not have lung cancer) = 4\(\%\)
  • P(Test gives positive and Subject has lung cancer) = 0.098\(\%\) this is also referred to as the joint probability of test being positive and the subject having lung cancer.

## Interactive Beta distribution PDF visualization 

Below you can find an interactive visualization of the probability density function of the Beta distribution.
You can set the two parameters of the beta distribution ($\alpha$ and $\beta$, see e.g. [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_distribution) for further details). This is only meant to help you get a feel for the Beta distribution, for subtask 3.a) you will still have to plot the density function yourself.

```{ojs}
//| code-fold: true

math = require('https://unpkg.com/mathjs@5.9.0/dist/math.min.js')
xs = d3.range(0, 1, 1e-3)
viewof alpha = Inputs.input(2)
viewof beta = Inputs.input(3) 
Inputs.form([
    Inputs.bind(
        Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 2, step: 0.1, label: "alpha"}),
        viewof alpha
    ), 
    Inputs.bind(
        Inputs.range([0, 10], {value: 3, step: 0.1, label: "beta"}), 
        viewof beta
    ),
], {
    template: (inputs) => htl.html`<div style="display: flex; gap: 3em">
  ${inputs}
</div>`
  })

class BetaDistribution {
    constructor(alpha, beta){
        this.alpha = alpha;
        this.beta = beta;
        this.normalizing_constant = math.gamma(alpha) * math.gamma(beta) / math.gamma(alpha + beta)
    }
    pdf(x){
        return Math.pow(x, alpha-1) * Math.pow(1 - x, beta-1) / this.normalizing_constant;
    }
    pdfs(x){
        return x.map(x => this.pdf(x));
    }
}
Plot.plot({
    marks: [
        Plot.line(d3.zip(xs, new BetaDistribution(alpha, beta).pdfs(xs))),
        Plot.ruleX([0]),
        Plot.ruleY([0]),
        Plot.text([`The PDF of the Beta(${alpha}, ${beta}) distribution`], {frameAnchor: "top", fontSize: 20, dy: -40})
    ],
    x: {label: "x"},
    y: {label: "PDF"},
    marginTop: 60, 
    style: {fontSize: "1em", width: "100%"},
})
```

# Bayes' theorem 1   
 
A group of researchers has designed a new  
inexpensive and painless test for detecting lung cancer. The test is
intended to be an initial screening test for the population in
general. A positive result (presence of lung cancer) from the test
would be followed up immediately with medication, surgery or more
extensive and expensive test. The researchers know from their
studies the following facts:

-   Test gives a positive result in 98$\%$ of the time when the test
    subject has lung cancer.
-   Test gives a negative result in 96 $\%$ of the time when the
    test subject does not have lung cancer.
-   In general population approximately one person in 1000 has lung
    cancer.

::: {.subtask}

The researchers are happy with these preliminary results (about
97$\%$ success rate), and wish to get the test to market as soon as
possible. How would you advise them? Base your answer on Bayes' rule
computations.

:::

Relatively high false negative (cancer doesn't get
